text.tspan: Natural Selection is very important for seeing the causes of Evolution
Sometimes Natural Selection is classified into multiple classes depending on its effects on the population
The graphs below illustrate the changes according to different types of natural selection
Directional Selection:
One phenotype is favored by environmental
conditions, and is not the average
phenotype (often the heterozygote).
Natural Selection will cause the population's
phenotypic ratios to skew towards the
selected phenotype as they will be more
likely to survive, reproduce, and pass their
traits to the next generation.
Stabilizing Selection:
The average phenotype is selected for, or other
phenotypes are selected against.
Natural Selection will cause the population to
decrease its spread in phenotypic ratios and
condense on the average trait (often the
heterozygote). Over generations, more individuals
will have the heterozygote genotype.
Disruptive Selection:
The average phenotype is selected against, or both
extremes are selected for.
Natural Selection will cause the population to
diverge into groups, representing the two bumps
on the graph. Since both extremes tend to have
similar fitnesses, both phenotypes will often
survive and often separate into separate groups
along with those of similar phenotype. In extreme
cases this may cause speciation or a reproductive
incompatibilities.
This mode of selection is much more rare.
Trevor
